tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcStiAhToVU_-TuwnWK1Rr9aT_suh6PNJkoaWg";s:8:"filetype";s:3:"png";s:5:"width";i:628;s:6:"height";i:1260;s:6:"source";s:49:"https://www.pinterest.com/pin/614248836658798920/";s:6:"domain";s:17:"www.pinterest.com";}}s:9:"sentences";a:56:{i:0;s:38:"Why chair conformation is most stable.";i:1;s:131:"The chair conformation is more stable because it does not have any steric hindrance or steric repulsion between the hydrogen bonds.";i:2;s:84:"By drawing cyclohexane in a chair conformation we can see how the Hs are positioned.";i:3;s:38:"These are hydrogens in the axial form.";i:4;s:42:"These hydrogens are in an equitorial form.";i:5;s:38:"Why are chairs more stable than boats.";i:6;s:73:"To gain more stability cyclohexane adopts the chair conformation instead.";i:7;s:155:"The chair conformation is a six-membered ring in which atoms 2 3 5 and 6 lie in the same plane atom 1 lies above the plane and atom 4 lies below the plane.";i:8;s:94:"With this conformation the bond angles are 1109 degrees much closer to the ideal 1095 degrees.";i:9;s:114:"So choosing the more stable chair conformation is straightforward when there is only one group on the cyclohexane.";i:10;s:59:"You just need to find the energy value for the axial group.";i:11;s:121:"However if there are more groups on the cyclohexane we need to take into consideration the 13-diaxial interaction of all.";i:12;s:50:"Thereof why is the chair conformation more stable.";i:13;s:131:"The chair conformation is more stable because it does not have any steric hindrance or steric repulsion between the hydrogen bonds.";i:14;s:84:"By drawing cyclohexane in a chair conformation we can see how the Hs are positioned.";i:15;s:38:"These are hydrogens in the axial form.";i:16;s:61:"Why is chair conformation more stable than boat conformation.";i:17;s:330:"It is clear from the above image that the boat conformation can be assumed as the trans isomer and the chair conformation can be assumed as cis isomer and we all knows that the cis isomer is more stable that the trans isomer because in the cis isomer the prior groups ae on the opposite side thus they feels the minimum repulsion.";i:18;s:262:"Chair conformation of cyclohexane is more stable than boat form because in chair conformaion the C-H bonds are equally axial and equatorial ie out of twelve C-H bonds six are axial and six are equatorial and each carbon has one axial and one equatorial C-H bond.";i:19;s:129:"The fact that the methyl group is on an axial bond will ultimately determine which of these two chair conformers are more stable.";i:20;s:74:"Ideally more stable chairs wil have the larger groups on equatorial bonds.";i:21;s:55:"As you can see that is what happens in the first chair.";i:22;s:135:"For the second chair the methyl groups position on an axial bond will cause steric strain which will reduce the stability of the chair.";i:23;s:68:"I am asked to draw the most stable chair conformation of compound 1.";i:24;s:85:"After doing so I am a little uncertain which of the conformations is the most stable.";i:25;s:92:"The most stable conformation is the one where the most bulky group is positioned equatorial.";i:26;s:32:"Figure-3 represents less stable.";i:27;s:47:"There are 2 chair conformation of the molecule.";i:28;s:76:"Second one is less stable than first one because of the presence of 1 3 D i.";i:29;s:92:"Conformer B for 1R-33-dichlorocyclohexanol is lower energy and more stable than conformer A.";i:30;s:160:"The following guidelines can be used to determine the percent distribution of two chair conformers using the Gibbs free energy equation and some simple algebra.";i:31;s:94:"A chair conformation is one of many conformations of a cyclohexane ring and it is most stable.";i:32;s:34:"It has equatorial and axial bonds.";i:33;s:34:"It has equatorial and axial bonds.";i:34;s:122:"The equatorial bonds e are perpendicular to the axis of the ring while axial bonds a are parallel to the axis of the ring.";i:35;s:262:"Chair conformation of cyclohexane is more stable than boat form because in chair conformaion the C-H bonds are equally axial and equatorial ie out of twelve C-H bonds six are axial and six are equatorial and each carbon has one axial and one equatorial C-H bond.";i:36;s:121:"The conformations that faces least steric hindrance and less torsional as well as angle strain is said to be more stable.";i:37;s:262:"Chair conformation of cyclohexane is more stable than boat form because in chair conformaion the C-H bonds are equally axial and equatorial ie out of twelve C-H bonds six are axial and six are equatorial and each carbon has one axial and one equatorial C-H bond.";i:38;s:79:"This leads to a staggered conformation in chair form reducing torsional strain.";i:39;s:124:"The tert-butyl group needs to be placed in the equatorial bond as it is the lowest energy or highest stability conformation.";i:40;s:123:"If the tert-butyl group is placed in the axial bond then the chair has the highest energy or the least stable conformation.";i:41;s:74:"Always place the largesthighest priority group in the equatorial position.";i:42;s:27:"What is Chair Conformation.";i:43;s:63:"Chair conformation is the most stable structure of cyclohexane.";i:44;s:34:"This is because it has low energy.";i:45;s:100:"Usually at room temperature around 25C all the molecules of cyclohexane occur in chair conformation.";i:46;s:72:"1 The most stable conformation of cyclohexane is the chair conformation.";i:47;s:73:"2 There is no angle or torsional strain in the chair form of cyclohexane.";i:48;s:113:"In a chair conformation Fig1 all of the carboncarbon bond angles are 1095 o and are thereby free of angle strain.";i:49;s:70:"The chair conformation is the most stable conformation of cyclohexane.";i:50;s:76:"I n chair cyclohexane there are two types of positions axial and equatorial.";i:51;s:131:"The axial positions point perpendicular to the plane of the ring whereas the equatorial positions are around the plane of the ring.";i:52;s:197:"By contrast in the chair form of cyclohexane the Newman reveals that all of the hydrogens and carbons are staggered as you look along each C-C bond which is a considerably more stable conformation.";i:53;s:56:"The difference between the two forms is about 102 kJmol.";i:54;s:222:"Least stable chair Most stable chair 1 1 1 √ê18 kcalmolG b Chlorocyclohexane also exists in two different chair conformations one of which is 06 kcalmol more stable than the other ie the A value for the chloro group is 06.";i:55;s:31:"In each of the two boxes below.";}}